        "title": "Write the law and build the altar — inscription and sacrifice as inseparable covenant acts",
        "range": "27:1-8",
        "excerpt": "You shall set up for yourself large stones and coat them with lime and write on them all the words of this law... Moreover, you shall build there an altar to the LORD your God, an altar of stones.",
        "body": "Moses opens with an unprecedented command: when Israel crosses the Jordan, before building a city, before establishing a court, before any structure of settled life, they are to erect large stones, coat them with lime (*sid*), and inscribe the entire law on them (27:2-3). Ancient Near Eastern parallels — the Hammurabi stele, Egyptian boundary stelae — show that lime-plastered standing stones were used for permanent public proclamation. Moses commands the covenant terms to be the first public inscription in the land. The land itself will bear the law's text before it bears any Israelite institution.\n\nThe law-stones are assigned to Mount Ebal (27:4), the mountain of curse — not to Gerizim, the mountain of blessing. This is the chapter's first theological alert. The law is not placed on the side of optimism but on the side of honest reckoning. Israel enters the land knowing that the same law which promises blessing also threatens curse, and the permanent inscription is on the side that threatens. Swindoll observes that Moses's constant insistence on clarity and memory is pastoral — the generation that will live in the land must never forget that they entered it as recipients of grace under a law they cannot perfectly keep.\n\nAlongside the law-stones, Moses commands an altar of uncut stones (27:5-7). The prohibition of iron tools (27:5) echoes Exodus 20:25: human craft must not 'improve' what comes to God in worship. The altar receives both burnt offerings (*olah*, total dedication — the entire animal consumed) and peace offerings (*shelamim*, communion — the worshipper eats before God and rejoices). The collocation of law-inscription and dual sacrifice on the same mountain is not accidental liturgical planning; it is covenantal theology: the written demand of the law and the provision for those who fall short of it stand together on the same stone. Douglas Moo, commenting on the parallel in Galatians 3, notes that the altar at Ebal implies from the beginning that Israel's relationship to the law was always mediated by sacrifice.\n\nThe command to write 'very distinctly' (27:8) — *baar*, to make plain, to engrave clearly — is the chapter's insistence on transparency. The covenant terms must be legible to everyone who passes: no esoteric law known only to priests, no terms concealed from the governed. The entire Torah is to be publicly legible in the center of the land.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sid* (plaster, lime) — the same word used for whitewash, a hard surface that takes inscription and preserves it against weather. *Olah* (burnt offering) — from *alah*, to go up; the whole offering ascends in smoke to God. *Shelamim* (peace offerings) — from *shalom*, wholeness, completion; the communal meal that follows seals the covenant in shared table fellowship. *Baar* (write very distinctly) — to make clear, engrave plainly; the same root used in Habakkuk 2:2 ('write the vision and make it plain on tablets')."
