        "excerpt": "Cursed is he who does not confirm the words of this law by doing them. And all the people shall say, 'Amen.'",
        "body": "Deuteronomy 27 does not resolve its own crisis. It generates one. The chapter commands Israel to say 'Amen' to twelve curses, the last of which indicts everyone who fails to confirm the whole law by doing (27:26). The congregation obeys — and in obeying, implicates themselves. The chapter ends in this tension: the law is publicly inscribed, the altar is erected for sacrifice, the people are constituted as YHWH's covenant partner — and the last sound is the entire nation's voice agreeing that any failure to keep the whole law deserves the curse.\n\nPaul's reading in Galatians 3:10-13 is not a creative reinterpretation; it is the text's own logic followed to its terminus. If the law demands total confirmation by doing (Deuteronomy 27:26), and if 'there is none righteous, not even one' (Romans 3:10, citing Psalm 14), then everyone who has ever stood in the covenant stands under the curse they ratified. The law cannot save the very people it has enrolled in condemnation — not because the law is bad (Romans 7:12) but because the people are unable to confirm it (Romans 8:3).\n\nThe altar on Mount Ebal answers this crisis proleptically. Sacrifice — burnt offering for consecration, peace offering for communion — is placed precisely on the mountain where the curse stands, anticipating what Galatians 3:13 will declare: 'Christ redeemed us from the curse of the Law, having become a curse for us — for it is written, Cursed is everyone who hangs on a tree.' The altar at Ebal is not the solution; it points to the solution. The uncut stones that receive Israel's sacrifice foreshadow the cross planted in the earth — no human craftsmanship could make it more fit to receive what it must bear. The congregation's twelve 'Amens' are ultimately answered by one voice, the voice of the Son who said Amen to every curse in the book so that the people of God might say Amen to the blessing on Gerizim.\n\nFor the believer in Christ, Deuteronomy 27 functions as diagnosis and as comfort simultaneously. As diagnosis: the twelve curses are a mirror for the sins of the hidden heart — every reader should find themselves in the list. As comfort: the altar on Ebal is there before the curses are finished being read. Atonement is already provided on the mountain of curse. Tim Keller's observation is apt here: the gospel does not minimize the law's demand; it takes it with absolute seriousness and provides an advocate who has already borne what the demand requires."
